<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="134" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[828,1437,887,1166]" pageId="7" pageNumber="134">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,976,887,910]" pageId="7" pageNumber="134">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is widely distributed across Europe (
<bibRefCitation author="SCHEUCHL" box="[917,1079,919,942]" firstAuthor="SCHEUCHL" pageId="7" pageNumber="134" refId="ref8815" refString="SCHEUCHL E. 2000: Illustrierte Bestimmungstabellen der Wildbienen Deutschlands und Osterreichs. Band I: Anthophoridae. - 2. erweiterte Auflage. Erwin Scheuchl, Velden, 158 pp." type="book" year="2000">SCHEUCHL 2000</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="AMIET" box="[1087,1267,919,942]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="AMIET" pageId="7" pageNumber="134" refId="ref8315" refString="AMIET F., HERRMANN M., MULLER A. &amp; NEUMEYER R. 2007: Apidae 5. Ammobates, Ammobatoides, Anthophora, Biastes, Ceratina, Dasypoda, Epeoloides, Epeolus, Eucera, Macropis, Melecta, Melitta," type="book" year="2007">AMIET et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Its distribution extends to the Middle East and North Africa, and probably further into Asia. It is the only common and widespread species of this genus across Europe. It is more common in Northern and Central Europe, while in Southern Europe and the Middle East (as well as in 
<collectingCountry box="[1204,1282,1079,1102]" name="Turkey" pageId="7" pageNumber="134">Turkey</collectingCountry>
) other species (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eversmann" authorityYear="1852" box="[836,987,1112,1135]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Epeolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="134" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transitorius">
<emphasis box="[836,987,1112,1135]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="134">E. transitorius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Panzer" baseAuthorityYear="1799" box="[998,1115,1112,1135]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Epeolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="134" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cruciger">
<emphasis box="[998,1115,1112,1135]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="134">E. cruciger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, or local endemics) are usually more common.
</paragraph>
